00:00:10,820 --> 00:00:12,780
I want to be your friend again.

44
00:00:14,030 --> 00:00:15,980
W-why, Shaun? What happened?

45
00:00:15,980 --> 00:00:18,270
People need friends.

46
00:00:18,270 --> 00:00:19,220
Well...

47
00:00:20,650 --> 00:00:21,660
Yeah, they do.

48
00:00:22,780 --> 00:00:24,580
But you said you wanted me -

49
00:00:24,580 --> 00:00:26,730
to stop interfering, remember?

50
00:00:26,880 --> 00:00:28,620
You wanted space.

51
00:00:29,600 --> 00:00:31,740
You wanted - to make your own mistakes.

52
00:00:32,410 --> 00:00:34,790
I need a friend more than I need space.

53
00:00:38,900 --> 00:00:41,750
You were a good mentor and a good friend.

54
00:00:42,800 --> 00:00:44,450
Well, thank you, Shaun.

55
00:00:46,970 --> 00:00:49,690
You don't know how much it means to me to hear you say that.

56
00:00:50,820 --> 00:00:52,330
But I-I think...

57
00:00:55,730 --> 00:00:58,280
I think you may need a new mentor.

58
00:01:01,280 --> 00:01:02,160
I'm dying.

59
00:01:17,090 --> 00:01:19,190
12 to 18 months.

60
00:01:19,200 --> 00:01:22,500
I'd appreciate it - if you didn't tell anyone, okay?

61
00:01:22,500 --> 00:01:23,830
I-I will in my own time.

62
00:01:23,830 --> 00:01:26,000
Okay. Have you had a full work-up?

63
00:01:26,710 --> 00:01:27,850
Yes, of course.

64
00:01:27,850 --> 00:01:30,220
It could be a secondary tumor

65
00:01:30,220 --> 00:01:32,520
metastasized to your brain from somewhere else.

66
00:01:32,520 --> 00:01:33,880
It's the only tumor found.

67
00:01:33,880 --> 00:01:36,870
It could be an inflammatory or infectious process.

68
00:01:36,870 --> 00:01:38,520
It was a tumor, Shaun.

69
00:01:38,520 --> 00:01:39,870
You should get a second opinion.

70
00:01:39,870 --> 00:01:41,970
Shaun, I've been a neurosurgeon for 30 years.

71
00:01:41,970 --> 00:01:45,250
I think that qualifies as a second opinion.

72
00:01:45,530 --> 00:01:48,870
You should get a second opinion.

73
00:01:48,880 --> 00:01:49,520
You have to know whether --

74
00:01:49,520 --> 00:01:51,470
All right, all right, all right, all right, Shaun.

75
00:01:51,470 --> 00:01:52,860
I'll get a second opinion.

76
00:01:52,880 --> 00:01:53,730
Okay?

77
00:01:54,520 --> 00:01:55,170
Okay.

78
00:01:55,170 --> 00:01:56,980
Can I go to work now?

79
00:02:01,590 --> 00:02:03,670
Okay, Doctor, what's your diagnosis?

80
00:02:03,670 --> 00:02:04,880
I'm drunk.

81
00:02:04,950 --> 00:02:06,950
Not you. Other doctor.

82
00:02:08,850 --> 00:02:11,000
Uh, well, given the degree of the rotation

83
00:02:11,000 --> 00:02:13,220
and the fact that the break is almost compound,

84
00:02:13,220 --> 00:02:14,870
I'd say we're dealing with a Bimalleolar

85
00:02:14,870 --> 00:02:16,050
or Trimalleolar fracture.

86
00:02:16,050 --> 00:02:17,760
Very good. What else?

87
00:02:21,510 --> 00:02:22,240
Color?

88
00:02:23,660 --> 00:02:25,180
Blood flow is restricted.

89
00:02:25,450 --> 00:02:26,270
His foot's dying.

90
00:02:26,270 --> 00:02:27,960
Oh, no.

91
00:02:27,960 --> 00:02:30,440
I'm gonna have to reset it now. Hold his leg.

92
00:02:31,350 --> 00:02:33,190
- No.No, no, no. - No, it's okay.

93
00:02:33,200 --> 00:02:34,140
It's just gonna take a second.

94
00:02:34,140 --> 00:02:35,420
I need you to count to three.

95
00:02:35,910 --> 00:02:36,550
One...

96
00:02:36,550 --> 00:02:38,830
One, two --

97
00:02:44,520 --> 00:02:46,130
Is Caden's leg gonna be okay?

98
00:02:46,450 --> 00:02:48,080
How long has his leg been like this

99
00:02:48,080 --> 00:02:49,500
and how exactly did it happen?

100
00:02:49,660 --> 00:02:52,060
Well, he's been like that since I found him.

101
00:02:52,060 --> 00:02:54,430
He probably tripped over a curb or something

102
00:02:54,430 --> 00:02:56,490
because that's where he was.

103
00:02:56,670 --> 00:02:58,630
Any reason you felt the need to tell me twice

104
00:02:58,630 --> 00:02:59,770
that you found him like this?

105
00:03:00,280 --> 00:03:01,970
Dr. Park, boy's going to surgery.

106
00:03:01,970 --> 00:03:02,970
You're going with.

107
00:03:03,780 --> 00:03:04,990
Don't go anywhere.

108
00:03:15,990 --> 00:03:18,580
Shouldn't I be asleep for this?

109
00:03:18,590 --> 00:03:21,790
Your blood alcohol level complicates anesthesia

110
00:03:21,790 --> 00:03:23,580
and we think you have a concussion,

111
00:03:23,580 --> 00:03:25,820
so we're gonna keep you responsive.

112
00:03:25,820 --> 00:03:27,430
We did give you a regional nerve block,

113
00:03:27,430 --> 00:03:29,270
so you shouldn't feel anything.

114
00:03:33,090 --> 00:03:33,840
Cool.

115
00:03:33,870 --> 00:03:37,000
Bend the LCP plate over two degrees on the proximal end.

116
00:03:37,040 --> 00:03:38,270
Contouring pliers.

117
00:03:44,450 --> 00:03:45,910
BP is dropping, heart rate's rising.

118
00:03:45,910 --> 00:03:48,390
Let's tube him. IV fluids and phenylephrine, stat.

119
00:03:48,680 --> 00:03:51,470
We need to abort until we can get a handle on what else is going on.

120
00:03:51,470 --> 00:03:54,310
Give me a full body CT, full blood panels, and an echo.

121
00:03:54,310 --> 00:03:56,610
I think Jared and I may be able to dig up an answer quicker.

122
00:03:56,610 --> 00:03:58,040
Great. Get on it.

123
00:05:01,720 --> 00:05:02,870
Come up with anything?

124
00:05:04,710 --> 00:05:05,860
Neither did I.

125
00:05:07,660 --> 00:05:11,140
I had a friend, a neurosurgeon, at SF Muni.

126
00:05:11,520 --> 00:05:12,880
She looked at the scans.

127
00:05:12,890 --> 00:05:15,710
She came to the same diagnosis, Shaun.

128
00:05:15,710 --> 00:05:18,570
I have an inoperable glioma.

129
00:05:19,090 --> 00:05:19,880
Okay?

130
00:05:31,310 --> 00:05:33,340
I think you should go back to work, yes?

131
00:05:38,250 --> 00:05:40,070
I need to go to work.

132
00:05:47,350 --> 00:05:48,490
Be reasonable.

133
00:05:48,690 --> 00:05:49,560
Beg your pardon?

134
00:05:49,810 --> 00:05:51,210
Be reasonable.

135
00:05:51,220 --> 00:05:52,970
I have no idea what you're talking about.

136
00:05:52,970 --> 00:05:54,200
Oh, it'll be clear.

137
00:05:54,640 --> 00:05:55,580
What the hell happened to Caden?

138
00:05:55,580 --> 00:05:57,050
I -- I don't know. He twisted his ankle. I --

139
00:05:57,050 --> 00:05:58,310
You lied to me before.

140
00:05:58,310 --> 00:06:00,650
You're lying to me now, you spoiled little coward.

141
00:06:01,560 --> 00:06:02,580
Be reasonable.

142
00:06:03,520 --> 00:06:04,200
His friend's hurt.

143
00:06:04,200 --> 00:06:05,820
He's scared, and you're freaking him out.

144
00:06:17,160 --> 00:06:18,890
He's angry, but he's not wrong.

145
00:06:19,630 --> 00:06:21,620
Caden's in bad shape, and we don't know why.

146
00:06:22,720 --> 00:06:23,950
We need to know what happened.

147
00:06:26,730 --> 00:06:28,640
No, no, don't -- don't worry about him.

148
00:06:28,840 --> 00:06:29,690
Talk to me.

149
00:06:30,820 --> 00:06:32,000
You tell me the truth.

150
00:06:32,190 --> 00:06:35,170
You won't get in trouble. You'll just...help a friend.

151
00:06:36,890 --> 00:06:37,600
All right.

152
00:06:39,660 --> 00:06:40,720
We were pledging.

153
00:06:41,130 --> 00:06:43,540
And there's -- there's this, uh, wheel of torture thing

154
00:06:43,540 --> 00:06:45,370
you got to do for initiation.

155
00:06:46,020 --> 00:06:48,480
- Torture? - But it's mos-- - it's mostly stupid stuff, dude.

156
00:06:48,480 --> 00:06:50,870
It's, like, like, drink a cup of olive oil

157
00:06:50,870 --> 00:06:53,430
or eat a tablespoon of cinnamon.

158
00:06:53,430 --> 00:06:54,770
And what did Caden land on?

159
00:06:54,770 --> 00:06:55,740
Laundry.

160
00:06:56,050 --> 00:06:57,250
He had to do laundry?

161
00:06:57,280 --> 00:07:01,630
No, like, like, he had to, uh, eat th-those laundry things,

162
00:07:02,020 --> 00:07:04,310
as many as he could in 30 seconds.

163
00:07:04,310 --> 00:07:06,330
Detergent? Eat detergent?

164
00:07:06,420 --> 00:07:07,640
And how many did he have?

165
00:07:07,970 --> 00:07:10,790
I don't know. Like six, maybe seven, seven.

166
00:07:11,580 --> 00:07:12,860
He ate detergent.

167
00:07:13,260 --> 00:07:14,980
Could've burned a hole through his esophagus

168
00:07:14,980 --> 00:07:17,120
or his stomach and intestines.

169
00:07:22,170 --> 00:07:23,620
Catch that bleeder, please.

170
00:07:24,780 --> 00:07:26,250
Let's hope he doesn't breed.

171
00:07:27,780 --> 00:07:29,730
What? He isn't an idiot?

172
00:07:29,920 --> 00:07:31,910
We have healthy bowel attached to healthy bowel.

173
00:07:31,910 --> 00:07:32,720
Let's close him up.

174
00:07:32,720 --> 00:07:33,830
Dr. Melendez?

175
00:07:33,830 --> 00:07:36,290
The trauma S.O.D. is asking for you in O.R. Number 2.

176
00:07:36,290 --> 00:07:38,020
We got an emergency thoracotomy.

177
00:07:38,210 --> 00:07:39,850
Who can give me - the remaining steps for closing?

178
00:07:39,860 --> 00:07:41,230
Cut anchoring sutures, clear laps,

179
00:07:41,230 --> 00:07:42,180
and reposition the bowel.

180
00:07:42,180 --> 00:07:43,950
Remove clamps from the duodenal resection site,

181
00:07:43,950 --> 00:07:45,550
keeping clear of the underlying aorta,

182
00:07:45,550 --> 00:07:47,560
close the fascia using a looped 0 monofilament,

183
00:07:47,560 --> 00:07:49,790
close the dermal layer, then reapproximate the skin.

184
00:07:51,540 --> 00:07:54,990
Also, you need to ensure no omentum is caught

185
00:07:55,000 --> 00:07:56,790
in the fascial suture line.

186
00:07:57,810 --> 00:07:58,580
Close him up.

187
00:07:59,530 --> 00:08:00,710
Murphy, you're lead.

188
00:08:04,760 --> 00:08:06,590
Clearing laps.

189
00:08:09,150 --> 00:08:11,780
I will hold the repaired segment in place

190
00:08:11,780 --> 00:08:14,500
while you run the bowel for me.

191
00:08:20,600 --> 00:08:23,840
Bowel is clear - and ready to be repositioned.

192
00:08:28,720 --> 00:08:29,490
Shaun?

193
00:08:31,140 --> 00:08:32,700
Shaun, is everything all right?

194
00:08:34,450 --> 00:08:36,830
I lost something.

195
00:08:36,830 --> 00:08:37,950
In the cavity?

196
00:08:38,470 --> 00:08:39,190
No.

197
00:08:39,200 --> 00:08:41,230
But I know where it is now.

198
00:08:53,790 --> 00:08:54,540
Shaun.

199
00:08:55,230 --> 00:08:57,800
I left my scalpel here earlier today.

200
00:08:58,920 --> 00:09:02,160
You should get Diffusion Tensor Imaging.

201
00:09:02,200 --> 00:09:03,300
A DTI?

202
00:09:04,570 --> 00:09:08,810
Masses are difficult to diagnose accurately.

203
00:09:12,870 --> 00:09:15,410
You should get more imaging.

204
00:09:17,560 --> 00:09:19,010
People make mistakes.

205
00:09:19,010 --> 00:09:20,450
That's not gonna happen, Shaun.

206
00:09:23,560 --> 00:09:25,500
My scalpel isn't here.

207
00:09:37,100 --> 00:09:38,170
What happened this time?

208
00:09:38,170 --> 00:09:39,440
He's got a bleed somewhere.

209
00:09:39,810 --> 00:09:41,050
I want a capsule endoscopy to check

210
00:09:41,050 --> 00:09:43,000
the entire length of the bowel for bleeding and leaks.

211
00:09:43,000 --> 00:09:45,320
And get me a complete coagulation and metabolic profile.

212
00:09:45,320 --> 00:09:46,190
On it.

213
00:09:54,890 --> 00:09:56,680
Dr. Glassman is dying.

214
00:09:56,680 --> 00:09:57,410
What?

215
00:10:00,070 --> 00:10:02,290
What do you mean? He seemed fine.

216
00:10:02,290 --> 00:10:06,060
They say he has a glioma.

217
00:10:06,620 --> 00:10:08,390
That's a brain tumor.

218
00:10:08,440 --> 00:10:12,760
And he won't do a DTI scan to confirm the diagnosis.

219
00:10:12,760 --> 00:10:13,910
Did he get a second opinion?

220
00:10:13,910 --> 00:10:17,730
He has, but delayed or missed

221
00:10:17,730 --> 00:10:19,530
or incorrect diagnosis

222
00:10:19,530 --> 00:10:22,130
has an occurrence rate of 10% to 20%.

223
00:10:22,430 --> 00:10:23,820
Doctors make mistakes.

224
00:10:23,820 --> 00:10:25,370
Shaun, I don't know what you want me to do.

225
00:10:25,370 --> 00:10:28,270
I-I want you to sit down.

226
00:10:30,070 --> 00:10:31,470
That's what people say

227
00:10:31,810 --> 00:10:35,300
when they want to tell you something important.

228
00:10:38,480 --> 00:10:39,170
The part about him dying,

229
00:10:39,170 --> 00:10:41,400
that wasn't the important part?

230
00:10:49,530 --> 00:10:51,300
He won't listen to me.

231
00:10:51,310 --> 00:10:53,130
He is stubborn.

232
00:10:53,130 --> 00:10:54,490
- That he is. - Stubborn.

233
00:10:54,490 --> 00:10:55,890
He will listen to you.

234
00:10:57,200 --> 00:10:59,870
Okay, you have known him longer,

235
00:11:00,210 --> 00:11:02,950
you're his friend, he trusts you.

236
00:11:02,950 --> 00:11:04,270
Shaun, I can't make him do anything, either.

237
00:11:04,280 --> 00:11:06,530
You -- Y-You're an attorney.

238
00:11:07,200 --> 00:11:10,420
I'm not skilled - at lying or manipulation.

239
00:11:12,300 --> 00:11:13,550
So you want me to what?

240
00:11:16,160 --> 00:11:17,630
You want me to manipulate him?

241
00:11:19,510 --> 00:11:21,860
You want me to use our relationship and our history -

242
00:11:21,860 --> 00:11:25,170
to trick him into doing this?

243
00:11:27,910 --> 00:11:28,960
Yes, please.

244
00:11:35,620 --> 00:11:37,590
I knew you wouldn't let him die.

245
00:11:40,610 --> 00:11:43,980
Our patient has Disseminated Intravascular Coagulation.

246
00:11:43,980 --> 00:11:46,000
Can anyone tell me why that is very bad?

247
00:11:46,190 --> 00:11:48,090
Blood clots form throughout the blood vessels

248
00:11:48,090 --> 00:11:50,170
and rapidly deplete the body's clotting factors,

249
00:11:50,170 --> 00:11:51,810
thereby causing a systematic bleed.

250
00:11:51,810 --> 00:11:53,430
It's also a catch-22.

251
00:11:53,440 --> 00:11:54,830
If we treat the clotting,

252
00:11:54,830 --> 00:11:56,410
he might end up with a terminal bleed.

253
00:11:56,410 --> 00:11:58,570
And if we treat the bleeding, he'll have a terminal clot.

254
00:11:58,570 --> 00:11:59,830
So how do we treat it?

255
00:11:59,830 --> 00:12:01,900
We figure out the cause. Treat the cause.

256
00:12:01,900 --> 00:12:03,430
More damage from the detergent?

257
00:12:03,430 --> 00:12:04,680
Margins were clear. It's not that.

258
00:12:04,680 --> 00:12:06,270
He could have a crush injury from his ankle.

259
00:12:06,270 --> 00:12:08,940
Or a bacterial infection he picked up before or during surgery.

260
00:12:08,940 --> 00:12:10,580
It might have been set off by drug use.

261
00:12:10,580 --> 00:12:12,010
Or we did this to him.

262
00:12:15,400 --> 00:12:17,060
And by "We," I mean Shaun.

263
00:12:17,970 --> 00:12:20,320
He spaced out in the O.R. when he was closing,

264
00:12:20,360 --> 00:12:21,660
kind of like he is now.

265
00:12:21,660 --> 00:12:23,840
- I'm listening. - Comforting.

266
00:12:23,840 --> 00:12:24,910
He wasn't focused.

267
00:12:24,910 --> 00:12:26,230
He could've nicked a vessel, which could've caused --

268
00:12:26,230 --> 00:12:27,730
Okay, we're talking about Shaun.

269
00:12:27,730 --> 00:12:31,780
Yeah, he's quiet, but he was focused.

270
00:12:31,780 --> 00:12:32,950
He's always focused.

271
00:12:33,210 --> 00:12:35,560
His stitches look like they came out of a sewing machine.

272
00:12:36,990 --> 00:12:38,910
All right. Complications happen.

273
00:12:38,910 --> 00:12:40,820
The kid was in pretty bad shape when we got him.

274
00:12:40,820 --> 00:12:44,050
Physician error is way down on the list of likely causes.

275
00:12:44,050 --> 00:12:45,270
Crush trauma being top.

276
00:12:45,270 --> 00:12:48,650
Get him started on fresh frozen plasma and crystalloid fluids.

277
00:12:55,250 --> 00:12:55,960
Yeah?

278
00:12:57,330 --> 00:12:58,380
You got a second?

279
00:12:59,350 --> 00:13:00,910
Well, that's an open question.

280
00:13:01,170 --> 00:13:02,550
What can I do for you?

281
00:13:04,310 --> 00:13:06,410
I got a patient with DIC.

282
00:13:06,930 --> 00:13:09,130
One of the possible causes is surgeon error.

283
00:13:09,140 --> 00:13:10,590
Your patient, your error?

284
00:13:10,590 --> 00:13:11,630
Shaun's.

285
00:13:12,340 --> 00:13:15,740
He got distracted - during surgery, spaced out.

286
00:13:16,730 --> 00:13:17,420
It's not like him.

287
00:13:17,430 --> 00:13:19,880
One place he never misses a beat is the O.R.

288
00:13:21,690 --> 00:13:23,830
Is there anything going on that I should know about?

289
00:13:27,390 --> 00:13:28,790
He got some bad news.

290
00:13:29,190 --> 00:13:30,040
About what?

291
00:13:30,570 --> 00:13:32,010
It's a personal matter.

292
00:13:32,870 --> 00:13:36,940
Shaun was distracted by a personal issue?

293
00:13:38,670 --> 00:13:40,020
What, did Lea come back?

294
00:13:41,750 --> 00:13:43,050
She have a new boyfriend?

295
00:13:43,910 --> 00:13:45,330
His cable get cut off?

296
00:13:46,520 --> 00:13:48,960
I have an inoperable glioma.

297
00:13:50,570 --> 00:13:51,730
18 months.

298
00:13:58,200 --> 00:13:59,600
Aaron, I am so sorry.

299
00:14:01,330 --> 00:14:02,160
Me, too.

300
00:14:04,300 --> 00:14:05,790
Is there anything I can do?

301
00:14:07,400 --> 00:14:08,500
I wish.

302
00:14:11,730 --> 00:14:12,930
You should've told me.

303
00:14:16,520 --> 00:14:18,230
Or at least you shouldn't have told him.

304
00:14:35,030 --> 00:14:37,280
His coagulation factors are still off.

305
00:14:37,490 --> 00:14:38,810
Crush trauma isn't the issue.

306
00:14:38,810 --> 00:14:40,380
And his tox screen came back clean.

307
00:14:40,390 --> 00:14:42,230
- It's not drugs, either. - We don't know that.

308
00:14:42,230 --> 00:14:43,840
He's had so many transfusions,

309
00:14:43,840 --> 00:14:46,410
the blood in his veins isn't the same blood he came in with.

310
00:14:46,410 --> 00:14:47,990
The drugs could still be in his organs causing --

311
00:14:47,990 --> 00:14:49,200
I get that you don't want to think

312
00:14:49,200 --> 00:14:50,500
that this could be caused by your friend, but we have to --

313
00:14:50,500 --> 00:14:53,180
The kid came directly from a frat hazing, hammered.

314
00:14:53,180 --> 00:14:54,940
What are the odds he wasn't on drugs?

315
00:14:55,310 --> 00:14:56,920
We should start IV midazolam

316
00:14:56,920 --> 00:14:58,080
and sodium bicarbonate to counteract --

317
00:14:58,080 --> 00:14:59,770
That's the treatment for amphetamines.

318
00:14:59,770 --> 00:15:00,640
If you're wrong,

319
00:15:00,650 --> 00:15:02,340
that could cause a fatal arrhythmia.

320
00:15:02,340 --> 00:15:03,910
I'll find out what drugs he's on.

321
00:15:09,100 --> 00:15:10,520
You're going to find out by asking?

322
00:15:10,520 --> 00:15:12,050
Blake was honest with me before.

323
00:15:12,050 --> 00:15:13,070
It's a lot easier to be honest

324
00:15:13,070 --> 00:15:14,600
when you're not confessing to a crime.

325
00:15:14,600 --> 00:15:16,390
We don't have a lot of choice in the matter.

326
00:15:18,830 --> 00:15:20,000
That's not true.

327
00:15:22,450 --> 00:15:23,910
Thanks for doing this.

328
00:15:24,920 --> 00:15:26,040
Yeah, no worries.

329
00:15:27,320 --> 00:15:29,440
Noticed it was cut when I first saw you.

330
00:15:29,440 --> 00:15:30,940
Figured it should get cleaned up.

331
00:15:33,760 --> 00:15:35,150
Is it all right if I draw some blood?

332
00:15:35,420 --> 00:15:35,920
Just want to make sure

333
00:15:35,920 --> 00:15:37,730
you don't have any toxins or infections.

334
00:15:37,730 --> 00:15:38,540
Sure.

335
00:15:41,430 --> 00:15:42,370
So,

336
00:15:42,650 --> 00:15:46,910
the nurse said that Caden has DIC.

337
00:15:48,110 --> 00:15:49,200
Do you know what that is?

338
00:15:50,640 --> 00:15:52,490
Well, in short, his body is clotting

339
00:15:52,490 --> 00:15:53,990
and hemorrhaging at the same time.

340
00:15:54,550 --> 00:15:56,130
If we can't figure out what's causing it,

341
00:15:56,130 --> 00:15:57,050
he'll die.

342
00:16:02,580 --> 00:16:04,080
Just hold that there for me.

343
00:16:05,330 --> 00:16:06,190
All done.

344
00:16:09,920 --> 00:16:11,490
Blake, buddy, you're on something.

345
00:16:11,490 --> 00:16:12,320
Your pupils are dilated,

346
00:16:12,320 --> 00:16:14,620
and you're sweating in a 68-degree room.

347
00:16:14,620 --> 00:16:15,990
Now, I can hand this over to the cops

348
00:16:16,000 --> 00:16:18,940
or you can tell the truth about what Caden's on.

349
00:16:21,250 --> 00:16:21,970
Molly.

350
00:16:25,480 --> 00:16:27,600
I would've told you the truth if you'd asked.

351
00:16:29,720 --> 00:16:30,440
I'm sorry.

352
00:16:32,700 --> 00:16:33,930
You have time to talk?

353
00:16:37,370 --> 00:16:38,190
Shaun told you.

354
00:16:38,190 --> 00:16:39,590
He did. Yeah.

355
00:16:39,900 --> 00:16:41,440
I wish I would've heard it from you.

356
00:16:41,820 --> 00:16:43,040
Yeah, I'm sorry.

357
00:16:43,720 --> 00:16:45,440
- We're friends. - I get it.

358
00:16:45,450 --> 00:16:47,420
- I want to be there for you. - What, are you mad at me?

359
00:16:47,420 --> 00:16:48,340
Yes.

360
00:16:49,740 --> 00:16:51,330
I'm supposed to be there for you.

361
00:16:51,330 --> 00:16:53,320
To do what? To do what exactly? Hold my hand?

362
00:16:53,320 --> 00:16:54,970
Yes, if that's what's needed.

363
00:16:54,970 --> 00:16:57,690
Okay, well, what I need is to be left alone, okay?

364
00:16:57,690 --> 00:16:58,740
Well, you told Shaun,

365
00:16:58,750 --> 00:17:00,780
so that was a brilliant strategy.

366
00:17:00,790 --> 00:17:02,090
Okay, okay, I get it.

367
00:17:02,090 --> 00:17:04,280
Stupid, stupid, stupid, stupid, okay?

368
00:17:04,280 --> 00:17:06,340
Sometimes when people are told they are dying,

369
00:17:06,340 --> 00:17:07,500
they do stupid things!

370
00:17:07,510 --> 00:17:10,730
Sometimes people around them do stupid things!

371
00:17:10,800 --> 00:17:12,180
Shaun told you to come here

372
00:17:12,180 --> 00:17:15,610
to try to convince me to get more imaging, right?!

373
00:17:16,890 --> 00:17:18,610
Aaron, you can't stop fighting.

374
00:17:21,950 --> 00:17:24,130
- Maddie wouldn't have wanted you to stop -- - Don't,

375
00:17:24,130 --> 00:17:26,110
don't, don't, don't you dare.

376
00:17:27,090 --> 00:17:28,160
Don't you dare.

377
00:17:31,390 --> 00:17:33,140
What are you gonna say, huh?

378
00:17:34,360 --> 00:17:36,070
That Maddie was a fighter?

379
00:17:38,510 --> 00:17:39,760
That she never quit?

380
00:17:48,630 --> 00:17:49,470
I'm sorry.

381
00:17:53,720 --> 00:17:54,520
Thank you.

382
00:17:59,300 --> 00:18:01,740
And you should get the DTI.

383
00:18:03,850 --> 00:18:04,850
Not for you.

384
00:18:06,030 --> 00:18:09,490
You've accepted your diagnosis.

385
00:18:10,410 --> 00:18:11,510
Shaun hasn't.

386
00:18:15,030 --> 00:18:15,950
He needs to.

387
00:18:21,760 --> 00:18:22,590
Hey, Neil.

388
00:18:22,920 --> 00:18:25,530
I heard there was a complication in one of your cases.

389
00:18:25,700 --> 00:18:26,750
Caden Hauley?

390
00:18:26,990 --> 00:18:29,970
Heard or have you been monitoring all of Murphy's cases?

391
00:18:29,970 --> 00:18:32,070
I monitor all my department's cases.

392
00:18:32,250 --> 00:18:33,930
18-year-old with DIC.

393
00:18:33,930 --> 00:18:35,300
Any idea what set it off?

394
00:18:35,300 --> 00:18:36,630
Complications happen.

395
00:18:37,730 --> 00:18:39,690
The kid was in pretty bad shape when he got to us.

396
00:18:40,040 --> 00:18:43,310
I'm also wondering why you were in two surgeries at once.

397
00:18:43,990 --> 00:18:45,950
You left three first-years unattended?

398
00:18:47,570 --> 00:18:49,240
You know we do this all the time.

399
00:18:49,240 --> 00:18:51,280
We couldn't function efficiently if we didn't.

400
00:18:53,700 --> 00:18:55,130
I hope Caden pulls through.

401
00:19:02,700 --> 00:19:05,670
You got a very quick appointment.

402
00:19:06,580 --> 00:19:08,680
I have connections, Shaun.

403
00:19:10,060 --> 00:19:13,450
Why did you listen to Jessica but not me?

404
00:19:13,870 --> 00:19:15,590
Well, Jessica's pretty smart, too.

405
00:19:15,590 --> 00:19:18,240
Yes, but what did she tell you?

406
00:19:19,180 --> 00:19:20,680
I don't think this is a good time.

407
00:19:20,680 --> 00:19:21,940
When is a good time?

408
00:19:24,130 --> 00:19:25,660
I have a lot to learn from you,

409
00:19:25,660 --> 00:19:28,630
and if you're dying, less than two years to learn.

410
00:19:32,380 --> 00:19:34,010
Sorry to keep you waiting.

411
00:19:34,430 --> 00:19:37,140
There were some surprises on your images.

412
00:19:37,160 --> 00:19:39,180
The previous diagnosis was incorrect.

413
00:19:39,180 --> 00:19:43,500
You have a Glioblastoma Multiforme located in your pons.

414
00:19:44,410 --> 00:19:45,810
I'm sure I don't need to tell you this,

415
00:19:45,810 --> 00:19:49,480
but it's the most aggressive form of brain cancer.

416
00:19:50,870 --> 00:19:55,500
We estimate three, maybe four months.

417
00:19:56,720 --> 00:19:59,460
I can have my assistant get in touch with you

418
00:20:00,620 --> 00:20:03,020
to refer you to a therapist when you're ready.

419
00:20:11,240 --> 00:20:13,500
He still has low blood pressure and thin blood,

420
00:20:13,500 --> 00:20:15,690
which means the treatment for the MDMA didn't work.

421
00:20:15,690 --> 00:20:17,260
So the Molly wasn't the problem?

422
00:20:17,260 --> 00:20:19,210
It certainly didn't help him, but now we think he --

423
00:20:19,210 --> 00:20:22,260
Our best guess is Caden has a bacterial infection.

424
00:20:24,130 --> 00:20:24,960
Thanks.

425
00:20:28,960 --> 00:20:29,990
DIC?

426
00:20:31,480 --> 00:20:32,580
What happened there?

427
00:20:33,210 --> 00:20:34,840
Uh, we're not sure yet.

428
00:20:35,000 --> 00:20:36,510
He was pretty sick when he came in.

429
00:20:36,510 --> 00:20:38,980
I guess sometimes complications just happen.

430
00:20:39,300 --> 00:20:40,580
Interesting choice of words.

431
00:20:40,580 --> 00:20:42,790
Eerily similar - to what Dr. Melendez said to me.

432
00:20:43,660 --> 00:20:45,780
Yeah, he said it during a differential.

433
00:20:45,780 --> 00:20:47,680
I guess the phrasing just stuck with me.

434
00:20:47,680 --> 00:20:49,790
It's not like Melendez to be that laissez-faire.

435
00:20:49,790 --> 00:20:52,000
He usually likes to know exactly why things happen.

436
00:20:52,000 --> 00:20:53,610
One of the traits I admire about him.

437
00:20:53,610 --> 00:20:55,560
Yeah, well, we're trying to figure it out.

438
00:20:55,690 --> 00:20:58,030
But so far, - the cultures are negative.

439
00:20:58,030 --> 00:20:59,820
Shaun's closing was textbook.

440
00:20:59,820 --> 00:21:01,720
Drug use doesn't seem to be a problem.

441
00:21:03,630 --> 00:21:05,400
I didn't realize Murphy did the closing.

442
00:21:06,140 --> 00:21:07,120
Good for him.

443
00:21:29,040 --> 00:21:30,150
Oh, my God.

444
00:21:30,150 --> 00:21:31,080
Shaun.

445
00:21:31,180 --> 00:21:35,230
Yes, yes, there are - many different explanations.

446
00:21:35,230 --> 00:21:38,200
You asked me to get a second opinion. I got a second opinion.

447
00:21:38,560 --> 00:21:40,710
You asked me to get more imaging. I got more imaging.

448
00:21:40,710 --> 00:21:42,160
Shaun, you have to accept --

449
00:21:42,160 --> 00:21:43,990
No, I don't accept.

450
00:21:43,990 --> 00:21:46,040
I don't accept. I was right.

451
00:21:46,040 --> 00:21:48,220
No, you were not right. I'm dying, Shaun.

452
00:21:48,220 --> 00:21:49,790
I said doctors make mistakes...

453
00:21:49,490 --> 00:21:51,510
- Yeah, they made a mistake. - and they made a mistake.

454
00:21:50,530 --> 00:21:53,050
{\an8}I have less time than we even thought!

455
00:21:51,510 --> 00:21:54,430
Shaun was right. Shaun was right.

456
00:21:54,530 --> 00:21:56,410
Imaging is unreliable.

457
00:21:56,410 --> 00:21:57,590
The imaging that you asked me to get.

458
00:21:57,590 --> 00:22:00,970
Imaging is subject to interpretation.

459
00:22:01,690 --> 00:22:04,900
Yes, studies have shown that experts rely on --

460
00:22:05,070 --> 00:22:07,230
on -- on subjective measures

461
00:22:07,230 --> 00:22:10,070
- based on experience rather than object - No more.

462
00:22:10,070 --> 00:22:11,490
- Rather than objective - No more, no.

463
00:22:11,490 --> 00:22:12,930
No. No, no. No more. No more.

464
00:22:12,930 --> 00:22:15,120
- No more. - Many theories consistent with --

465
00:22:15,120 --> 00:22:17,310
You can do a biopsy to confirm

466
00:22:17,310 --> 00:22:18,740
because many tumors look alike.

467
00:22:18,740 --> 00:22:20,230
Some are treatable.

468
00:22:20,250 --> 00:22:22,950
- Some are curable. - Stop, will ya?!

469
00:22:22,950 --> 00:22:24,200
Some are curable. They're curable.

470
00:22:24,200 --> 00:22:26,880
Stop, please, will ya?! Stop, stop, stop talking!

471
00:22:26,880 --> 00:22:28,400
- Stop! - Okay.

472
00:22:28,440 --> 00:22:29,590
Stop!

473
00:22:33,740 --> 00:22:36,010
I am not hurting you.

474
00:22:36,020 --> 00:22:37,580
Oh, my God, stop.

475
00:22:37,900 --> 00:22:39,360
I'm helping you.

476
00:22:39,360 --> 00:22:41,320
No, you're not. You're not helping.

477
00:22:42,230 --> 00:22:44,490
I don't need theories.

478
00:22:45,310 --> 00:22:46,940
I don't need white boards.

479
00:22:46,940 --> 00:22:48,750
I don't need doctors!

480
00:22:49,060 --> 00:22:51,820
I don't want to think about the tumor!

481
00:22:51,830 --> 00:22:54,120
I don't want to think about dying!

482
00:22:54,680 --> 00:22:55,490
You know what I want?

483
00:22:55,490 --> 00:22:57,550
You know what I actually want? I want to -- I want to --

484
00:22:57,550 --> 00:22:59,570
I want to go - on a long drive somewhere.

485
00:22:59,580 --> 00:23:01,170
I want to -- I want to eat pancakes.

486
00:23:01,170 --> 00:23:02,510
I want to watch football.

487
00:23:02,510 --> 00:23:05,050
- It's not football season. - Oh, my God.

488
00:23:05,050 --> 00:23:06,910
I know - it's not football season.

489
00:23:10,140 --> 00:23:13,100
Do you mean you want to have fun?

490
00:23:17,980 --> 00:23:18,820
Yeah.

491
00:23:20,200 --> 00:23:21,400
I want to have fun.

492
00:23:24,940 --> 00:23:26,480
So you can keep fighting.

493
00:23:27,780 --> 00:23:29,330
Keep fighting if you want.

494
00:23:30,580 --> 00:23:33,810
It's futile and it's stupid.

495
00:23:36,900 --> 00:23:38,240
Or you can come with me.

496
00:24:04,350 --> 00:24:05,490
How long has he been hypoxic?

497
00:24:05,490 --> 00:24:07,000
It came on suddenly five minutes ago.

498
00:24:07,010 --> 00:24:09,510
He's on 100% high-flow oxygen, and his numbers aren't budging.

499
00:24:09,510 --> 00:24:11,340
He's ventilating fine.

500
00:24:11,770 --> 00:24:14,000
He must have thrombosed his pulmonary artery.

501
00:24:14,000 --> 00:24:15,840
We need to dissolve this clot before his heart stops.

502
00:24:15,840 --> 00:24:17,270
- Jared, prep for jugular access. - On it.

503
00:24:17,270 --> 00:24:19,460
50 milligrams tPA. Infusion now.

505
00:24:19,650 --> 00:24:21,110
Let's go, let's go, let's go!

506
00:24:24,540 --> 00:24:26,580
Is this fun?

507
00:24:30,010 --> 00:24:33,240
The Saturday after Valentine's Day,

508
00:24:33,350 --> 00:24:34,500
her favorite day of the year,

509
00:24:34,500 --> 00:24:36,280
even more than her birthday.

510
00:24:36,710 --> 00:24:40,000
The Chamber of Commerce would decorate this place

511
00:24:40,430 --> 00:24:44,950
and put out a crappy buffet meal, hire a deejay,

512
00:24:45,620 --> 00:24:47,360
and I'd put on a tux,

513
00:24:47,750 --> 00:24:50,330
and she'd put on a yellow Belle dress,

514
00:24:51,040 --> 00:24:52,080
and she'd...

515
00:24:53,360 --> 00:24:56,690
pin my bow tie on me,

516
00:24:56,690 --> 00:25:00,680
and I'd pin a little yellow corsage on her.

517
00:25:01,160 --> 00:25:05,790
And we'd come and we'd eat and we'd -- and we'd dance.

518
00:25:05,810 --> 00:25:15,000
{\an1}BGM: Your Smiling Face by James Taylor

519
00:25:09,810 --> 00:25:12,480
{\an9}♪ Whenever I see your smiling face ♪

520
00:25:12,480 --> 00:25:14,500
{\an9}♪ I have to smile myself ♪

521
00:25:14,500 --> 00:25:17,280
{\an9}♪ Because I love you ♪

522
00:25:17,280 --> 00:25:18,500
{\an9}♪ Yes, I do ♪

523
00:25:19,180 --> 00:25:20,500
I love you, sweetie.

524
00:25:21,480 --> 00:25:22,960
I love you more.

525
00:25:23,220 --> 00:25:24,900
Oh, you think so, huh?

526
00:25:25,220 --> 00:25:26,460
Well, I'll tell you what.

527
00:25:26,730 --> 00:25:28,970
You can take how much you love me,

528
00:25:29,140 --> 00:25:30,800
which I know is quite a lot,

529
00:25:31,080 --> 00:25:34,590
and then you can double it, and then you can add 10,

530
00:25:34,990 --> 00:25:36,780
and that's how much I love you.

531
00:25:36,790 --> 00:25:43,370
